    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1943-10-01T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1943-10-01T03:00:00-05:00" n="554"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d554">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">811.2361/37: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chargé in the Soviet Union</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Hamilton</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1943-10-01T11:00:00+03:00"
                            >October 1, 1943—11 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received October 4—10:58 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1506. In a conversation on September 29 with the Chief of the American Section of
                    the Foreign Office inquiry was made whether any information had yet been
                    received concerning the crews of the seven American planes which landed recently
                    on Kamchatka. We were informed that the Soviet authorities there had been asked
                    to provide the names of the crew members and information concerning their
                    welfare but that no reply had yet been received and that we would be informed as
                    soon as the information was forthcoming.<note n="57" xml:id="d554fn57">Later on
                        October 1, the Chief of the American Section (Zarubin) told Mr. Hamilton
                        that all crew members were alive and well. On October 8 the names of the
                        crew members, written phonetically in Russian, were supplied by the
                        Commissariat for Foreign Affairs.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Hamilton</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
    </text>
